<HEADLINE>
FT  20 AUG 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow slips as week ends on
soft note
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US stocks ended a volatile week on a soft note yesterday, as a skittish bond
market held most share prices in check, writes Frank McGurty in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished off 0.32 at 3,755.11, while the
more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 inched 0.51 forward to 463.68.
In the secondary markets, the Nasdaq composite edged 0.26 ahead to 742.43,
while the American SE composite outperformed the other indices, rising 1.90
to 445.45, Trading activity was moderate. Only 278m shares were exchanged on
the NYSE despite extra activity generated by the monthly expiration of
options on stock index futures and individual stocks. The 'double witching'
activity had a negligible impact on prices.
Indeed, investors struggled to find any source of inspiration. There was no
fresh economic news and the dollar, which had triggered declines in stocks
and bonds the previous session, held fairly steady against other leading
currencies.
The absence of news appeared to give a measure of support to the Treasury
market. But the benchmark 30-year government bond was showing losses for a
third straight day, reinforcing a negative tone that emerged in the
aftermath of Tuesday's move by the Federal Reserve to tighter money.
Stocks opened lower and drifted a shade under their opening values for most
of the morning. Just after midday, however, the leading indices nudged into
positive ground, only to recede again later.
The Dow industrial index would have fallen more sharply without another good
performance by IBM, which gained Dollars 1 7/8 to Dollars 68 1/8 .
A day earlier, Merrill Lynch raised its 1994 earnings projection for the
computer company, pushing its share price up to Dollars 66 7/8 . Yesterday
that valuation led Mr David Wu, an analyst at SG Warburg, to lift his price
target for the stock to at least Dollars 80 by mid-1985.
But most cyclical issues drifted. Among the most nota ble movers, Deere
dropped a further Dollars 1 to Dollars 65 7/8 while Navistar International,
up Dollars 1 at Dollars 15 7/8 , continued to benefit from a positive
earnings report.
In the energy sector, Mobil stood out with a Dollars 1 gain to Dollars 81
5/8 while JP Morgan's Dollars 1 1/8 decline to Dollars 63 1/4 was the
highlight in banking.
The NYSE's most actively traded issue was 20th Century Industries. The
insurance company dropped 22 per cent or Dollars 3 5/8 to Dollars 12 3/4
after a California court decided to allow a referendum designed to force a
cut in premiums charged by companies in the state.
Canada
Toronto stocks ended little changed in moderate trading with the TSE-300
composite index rising just 2.64 points, or 0.06 per cent, to 4,187.08, for
a gain on the week of about 12 points. Declines led advances 341 to 331 but
volume fell to 47.43m shares from 57.02m.
NOVA Corp. gained  1/4 to 13  1/4 . A Merrill Lynch analyst upgraded the
company to medium-term 'above average' from 'neutral.'
Royal Oak lost  1/8 to 5  1/2 , American Barrick added  1/4 to 30  7/8 and
Lac edged up  1/8 to 13  7/8 .
Mexico
Mexican equities ended firmer in the last session before presidential
elections scheduled for Sunday.
The IPC index of 37 leading shares closed 9.94 points higher just above the
psychological 2,700 point-barrier at 2,708.18, a gain of 0.37 per cent.
'The market was very firm all day,' one trader said. 'Investors remained
optimistic about the elections.'
Venezuela
Caracas stocks closed up sharply in brisk trading buoyed by the recent
plunge in domestic interest rates, traders said.
The independent Merinvest index rose 3.89 per cent to 144.10 on volume of
10m shares.
</TEXT>
