FT  20 AUG 94 / Scottish graduates accrue least debt
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
University students from Scotland who graduated this year were the most
solvent, a survey by Barclays Bank has found, John Authers writes.
The Scots owed only an average Pounds 900, partly because Scottish parents
were the most likely to pay their formal contribution, with 77 per cent
doing so in full, and because a higher proportion of Scottish students
attended a local university and lived at home.
The survey found students from the Midlands and north-west and north England
accumulated the heaviest debts. Midlands students who graduated this year
accumulated average debt of Pounds 2,371.
