<HEADLINE>
FT  20 AUG 94 / German tax on litter cleared
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Germany's city councils will be able to levy taxes on fast-food chains as a
means of reducing litter caused by wrapping, following a decision yesterday
by the Federal Administrative Court in Berlin, writes Judy Dempsey in
Berlin. The court ruled in favour of the city of Kassel, which in 1992
imposed a 50 pfennig (20 pence) tax on each disposable item made from
synthetic material. McDonalds and other fast-food outlets in Kassel had
challenged the decision on the grounds that the federal government, not
local councils, had sole right to raise taxation. The Kassel authorities,
which have raised DM1m a year through the surcharge, wanted to reduce the
city's 500m tonnes a year of rubbish.
