<HEADLINE>
FT  19 AUG 94 / London Stock Exchange: Footsie retreats after piercing the
3,200 mark - Market report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVE THOMPSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The FT-SE 100 Index successfully launched its expected attack on the 3,200
level, but it was hard won and quickly lost as the UK equity market
succumbed to repeated bouts of selling pressure in international bond
markets after disappointing economic news from the US.
The US news - in the form of a higher than forecast US international trade
deficit and worrying news from the Philadelphia Federal Reserve, which
published its August inflation index - caused a sharp downturn on Wall
Street shortly after the US market had opened.
The American data came hard on the heels of news that the Bundesbank council
had signalled no change in German interest rates.
At the close the FT-SE 100 was 7.7 down at 3,182.6, around two points off
the day's low. The FT-SE Mid 250, however, gave a more resolute performance,
closing only 1.3 easier at 3,740.4, thanks to some sustained institutional
support for the second-line stocks, which tended to get left behind the
leaders' upsurge on Wednesday.
Earlier, the equity market had shrugged off a poor start and pierced the
3,200 mark on the Footsie following yet more encouraging pointers on the
domestic economy.
This included a lower than expected rise in the broad money supply - up 4.8
per cent year-on-year against most forecasts of around 5.5 per cent - and a
marginally higher than forecast increase in retail sales in July. A 0.4 per
cent rise in sales came against market expectations of around 0.3 per cent.
Dealers said the latest data put the seal on a week of all-round excellent
news on the domestic economy and had headed off any lingering fears of an
early rise in UK interest rates.
On Wednesday the market raced ahead in the wake of a much better than
expected decline in the July inflation rate.
The market opened modestly easier, with most instititutions holding off
ahead of the Bundesbank meeting. The FT-SE 100 was some three points adrift
of its overnight level, but was never under real selling pressure and was
back in positive territory within an hour of the opening.
Early pressure was exerted by a big seller of the Footsie future, but a
measure of the market's resilience was that a brief decline to around the
3,189 level on the future triggered a powerful burst of support which kept
the contract above the so-called resistance level of 3,194 for the rest of
the session.
At its best, shortly after midday, the Footsie was up more than 11 points
and seemingly set fair, with market optimists still hopeful of a cut in
German interest rates. These hopes were fuelled throughout the morning by
news that German money supply in July had risen by 9.9 per cent fromn the
previous year, well down from the 11.4 per cent figure for June.
The absence of a German rate cut was the signal for a sharp decline in bonds
across the world, with UK gilts, around  1/4 higher shortly after the
opening, subsequently retreating to close with losses of around 3/4 at the
long end.
Equities moved down along with gilts, with the weak opening on Wall Street
producing more downside pressure on the market.
Marketmakers were by no means disheartened by the London market's
performance. 'We still feel okay, but all eyes are still firmly fixed on
bonds,' said one senior trader.
He emphasised that most marketmakers were trying to avoid taking big book
positions in such volatile markets. 'You only have to look at the big movers
to see where the marketmakers have been caught out.'
Turnover of 674m shares was regarded as slightly disappointing and well down
from Wednesday's 771.9m, which represented customer business worth Pounds
1.63bn.
</TEXT>
