<HEADLINE>
FT  19 AUG 94 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Lower than expected US trade figures combined with general profit-taking to
bring a retreat in stock index futures, pulling the near month Footsie
contract back below the 3,200 level, writes Joel Kibazo.
The opening trade in the September futures contract on the FT-SE 100 was
recorded at 3,205 and early profit-taking following Wednesday's strong run
saw it drift lower shortly after the opening.
The decision by the Bundesbank to leave its key interest rate figures
unchanged was quickly followed by a retreat in bond markets, triggering
active selling in September.
After briefly steadying ahead of lunchtime, the contract once again came
under pressure after the release of US economic data.
Dealers talked of a 'tired market after Wednesday's run', but there were
also reports of a big bear position in the market, with one dealer said to
have tried and failed to push the market lower.
September finished at 3,199, down 8 from its previous close and some 7
points ahead of its fair value premium to cash of around 10 points. Volume
was 12,828 lots.
The traded options remained buoyant ahead of today's expiry of the index
options. Total turnover was 47,883 contracts, of which 20,817 were dealt in
the FT-SE 100 option and 6,206 in the Euro FT-SE option.
</TEXT>
