<HEADLINE>
FT  19 AUG 94 / World Stock Markets (America): New inflation threat takes
Dow lower
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US stocks suffered a sharp setback yesterday as bonds retreated on fresh
signs of inflation, writes Frank McGurty in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 21.05 lower at 3,755.43 after
takeover speculation and Wall Street reratings had buffeted many individual
stocks. The more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 receded 2.00 to 463.17.
Volume on the Big Board came to 293.7m shares, with declining issues
outpacing rises by 1,287 to 346. In the secondary markets, the American SE
composite was off 1.39 at 443.55 and the Nasdaq composite 0.49 easier at
742.17.
From the opening, the optimism inspired by the Federal Reserve earlier in
the week showed further signs of erosion. Equities receded for a second day
as investors focused on the latest turn taken by the volatile bond market.
Although the Fed's decision to lift short-term interest rates was supposed
to have cleared the way for a sustained upturn, Treasury bonds tumbled again
on the news of mounting inflationary pressures.
The catalyst was the monthly survey conducted by the Federal Reserve Bank of
Philadelphia, which offered evidence that manufacturers were passing along
the higher cost of raw materials to customers. During the morning equities
suffered only modest losses. But bonds ploughed deeper into negative ground
and stocks were pulled down to near their session's lows in the late
afternoon.
Among the Dow industrials, International Business Machines and Coca-Cola
were two bright spots. IBM gained Dollars 1 3/8 at Dollars 66 1/4 after
Merrill Lynch raised its 1994 earnings and revenue projections. Coca-Cola
climbed Dollars 1 1/2 to Dollars 47 5/8 a day after it emerged that Mr
Warren Buffett had increased his stake in the company.
Offsetting those gains, Caterpillar was down Dollars 1 3/4 at Dollars 108
and General Motors shed Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 49 7/8 . Ford lost Dollars
1 1/8 at Dollars 29 1/2 and Chrysler fell Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 47 1/4 .
Deere gave back Dollars 1 1/8 at Dollars 66 7/8 after rising Dollars 2 1/2
in the previous session. But Navistar put on Dollars  7/8 at Dollars 14 7/8
as the truck and engine manufacturer posted improved third-quarter profits
and raised its projections of North American demand for heavy-duty trucks
this year.
Joy Technologies, which makes coal mining machinery, advanced Dollars 1 5/8
to Dollars 11 7/8 after agreeing to be acquired by Harnischfeger, a rival
supplier. News of the deal sent Harnischfeger's share price Dollars 1 1/4
lower to Dollars 22 1/8 .
Quaker Oats achieved a 52-week high of Dollars 82 1/8 after jumping Dollars
6, or 8 per cent. Investors were betting that a takeover was imminent. Two
other cereal makers also rang up big gains. Kellogg was Dollars 2 1/8 ahead
at Dollars 56 5/8 and General Mills added Dollars 1 5/8 at Dollars 55 3/8 .
In pharmaceuticals, Schering-Plough gave back Dollars 1 3/8 to finish at
Dollars 69 1/2 . Salomon Brothers said takeover speculation this month had
made the issue too expensive. Instead, excitement over the industry's
consolidation shifted to Mylan Laboratories, a generic drugs maker, boosting
its share price Dollars 2 1/8 to Dollars 26 1/8 .
The Nasdaq was held back by a Dollars 4 3/8 decline in Lotus Development's
share price to Dollars 41 3/8 . The selling followed cautious comments by at
least two Wall Street analysts.
Canada
Toronto shares lost ground as the US dollar weakened following Tuesday's
interest rate increases. Traders said market participants had expected the
US currency to rally after the rate rises, and were disappointed by its
performance.
The TSE 300 composite index declined 20.83 to 4,184.44, while falling issues
outnumbered advances by 407 to 311 after volume of 57.0m shares valued at
CDollars 681.9m.
All but one of the 14 stock groups declined, led by transportation and real
estate, which lost 1.83 and 1.63 per cent respectively. Consumer products
fell 1.30 per cent.
Mexico
Equities fluctuated before finishing marginally easier in mixed, volatile
trading ahead of the presidential election at the weekend.
The IPC index of 37 leading shares closed 1.41 points off at 2,698.24 after
moving within a 27-point range.
Brazil
Sao Paulo stocks were up 1.16 per cent at the close, but off the morning's
highs, as a rally founded on positive political and economic expectations
continued for the third straight session. The Bovespa index gained 576 at
50,266 in turnover of RDollars 486.5m (Dollars 543.6m).
</TEXT>
