<HEADLINE>
FT  19 AUG 94 / World Stock Markets (Asia Pacific): Region mixed, analysts
look at earnings prospects
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Share prices remained depressed for most of the day as the yen's rise above
the Y100 level against the dollar hurt investor confidence, but afternoon
buying led by dealers finally supported the Nikkei index, writes Emiko
Terazono in Tokyo.
The Nikkei 225 average closed 38.21 up at the day's high of 20,862.77 after
a low of 20,772.15. The yen's appreciation hit export-oriented electricals,
and the index declined in spite of buying by overseas investors. Late
index-linked demand from brokers eventually lifted shares.
Volume amounted to 266m shares, down from Wednesday's 356m. The Topix index
of all first section stocks lost a marginal 0.66 at 1,663.09 and the Nikkei
300 was off just 0.03 at 302.76. Declines led rises by 505 to 435, with 215
issues unchanged. In London the ISE/Nikkei 50 index slipped 4.54 to
1,349.14.
Overseas investors continued to buy steels and chemicals, but the gains were
eroded by profit-taking. Nippon Steel, the day's most active issue, eased Y1
to Y374 and Sumitomo Chemical dipped Y3 to Y575.
In spite of the low trading volumes, Nomura Securities advanced Y30 to
Y2,330, while other leading brokerages held steady. With average turnover
slowing to Y340bn per day, Baring Securities in Tokyo believed that earnings
at the Big Four houses - Nomura, Daiwa, Nikko and Yamaichi - and 10 second
tier brokers could be weaker than previous estimates based on a forecast of
daily turnover averaging Y450bn.
Meanwhile, Kleinwort Benson in Tokyo, which believed that turnover had
bottomed out, was advising investors to include in their portfolios
medium-sized brokerages with larger sensitivity to equity commissions.
Multimedia and telecommunications related stocks, which had been firmer on
Wednesday, lost ground as profits were taken. Victor dropped Y40 to Y1,350
and Nippon Telegraph and Telephone declined Y1,000 to Y879,000. DDI, the
long distance telecom operator listed on the second section, fell Y30,000 to
Y1m.
High-technology stocks were lower on the yen's rise: Toshiba receded Y5 to
Y764 and NEC Y10 to Y1,230.
Japan Airlines moved ahead Y13 to Y773 on buying led by foreign investors,
who expected the company to benefit from a restructuring plan, as well as
the sharp rise in overseas travel during the summer holidays.
In Osaka, the OSE average ended 17.40 down at 23,189.90 in volume of 44.1m
shares. Export-related shares declined, with Shima Seiki, a machinery maker,
losing Y100 at Y8,700.
Roundup
Following this week's increase in US interest rates - a move broadly
welcomed by the world's financial markets - analysts yesterday were
expecting investors in the south and south-east Asian region to concentrate
on earnings growth.
With the exception of Hong Kong, earnings in the region had generally
exceeded expectations, they said, assisted by relatively low inflation and
interest rates. No slowdown in growth was seen in Malaysia and Singapore in
1995, while Thailand and Indonesia were expected to see an acceleration in
earnings momentum.
The one exception to the positive picture was China: most brokers continued
to underweight the market in light of the economic and political
uncertainties overhanging equities.
SINGAPORE closed higher, boosted by buying of blue chips. The Straits Times
Industrial index gained 13.57 at 2,357.97. Analysts expected the market to
ease slightly soon, having strengthened 10 per cent since early July.
SEOUL was pushed up by selective interest in blue chips. Both Samsung
Electronics and Korea Mobile Telecom set record highs again, Samsung
advancing Won3,000 to Won104,400 and Korea Mobile rising the day's limit to
end Won10,000 up at Won420,000.
The composite index put on 3.52 at 946.48 and volume rose from 21.1m shares
to 30.5m.
TAIPEI fell sharply on heavy profit-taking by institutions. The weighted
index ended 59.74 lower at 6,586.16 and turnover was active at TDollars
107bn.
MANILA eased on a technical correction. The composite index shed 25.63 to
3,004.07, having peaked at 3,054 during the day. Bank of Philippine Islands,
one of the country's top five commercial banks, was the most heavily traded,
its shares falling 3.6 per cent to 1,060 pesos.
SYDNEY finished mildly firmer, overseas investors having encouraged a
recovery from a morning low. The All Ordinaries index was finally 7.3 up at
2,066.8 in volume of 153.7m shares as the market warmed to Wednesday's key
interest rate rise to 5.5 per cent. CRA jumped 22 cents to a record closing
high of ADollars 19.48.
WELLINGTON's NZSE-40 index softened 4.08 to 2,097.38 in thin turnover of
NZDollars 34m. INL slipped 9 cents to NZDollars 5.20 ahead of its annual
profits announcement today, which promises to be busy with half a dozen
companies due to report.
HONG KONG digested Wednesday's sharp gains and the US rate rise, while
investors took a close look at the prospects of an increase in domestic key
rates and how this would affect equities. Property shares were weak as the
Hang Seng index retreated 19.09 to 9,518.89 in turnover down from HKDollars
5.66bn to a preliminary total of HKDollars 3.50bn.
BOMBAY finished at a record closing high as buying by foreign investors and
speculators forced local mutual funds to stop their selling and keep to the
sidelines. The BSE index was ahead 27.83 at 4,534.33. Gujarat Ambuja Cement
rose Rs30 to Rs770 after the company announced a board meeting for today to
declare a scrip issue, its annual results and a dividend.
JAKARTA was led higher by a range of blue chips, closing 9.28, or 1.9 per
cent, better at 492.88. Analysts suggested that firm foreign sentiment and
local bullish interest were the market's main driving factors.
