<DATE>940819
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  19 AUG 94 / Commodities and Agriculture: China's cotton supply crisis
deepens
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY WALKER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BEIJING
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
China's cotton production will fall well short of demand this year,
according to a recent survey conducted by the country's State Statistical
Bureau. The shortfall seems likely to exacerbate chronic supply problems at
Chinese mills.
The bureau, which surveyed China's nine main cotton producing areas,
concluded that the area planted this year was between 5.26m and 5.55m
hectares.
A western agricultural attache said 5.3m ha would yield about between 4.6m
ant 4.7m tonnes, 10 per cent less than the country's domestic requirement.
But he also said it was difficult to forecast China's imports, which might
be as high as 400,000 tonnes, without details of the extent and condition of
its stockpile.
China's cotton sector was plunged into crisis earlier in the year with
textile mills throughout the country starved of supplies. An increase in the
international price, stockpiling by local authorities and corruption in the
state supply system worsened the problem. Dozens of mills were forced to
reduce output or stop production altogether, causing lay-offs of thousands
of employees.
Chinese media this week reported a fall of 34 per cent in state purchases of
cotton in the first quarter, indicating continuing supply problems.
Chinese farmers in the northern regions, which account for the bulk of
production, are also facing a threat from the boll worm infestation that has
wrecked crops in the past few years. China's cotton harvest slumped from
5.6m tonnes in 1991 to 3.7m tonnes last year, partly because the boll worm
has developed resistance to pesticides.
Cotton mills have been facing dual problems of lack of supply and poor
quality cotton, some of which has been adulterated deliberately to increase
its weight, according to Chinese media. Newspapers reported recently that to
secure a higher price suppliers, including state companies, had added to
cotton bails bricks, stones, oil, rice waste, sand, husks, glass and iron
chips. The Economic Daily said that a nation-wide inspection programme in
March found that only 55.26 per cent of cotton was usable, down from 78.46
per cent a year earlier.
Mr Huang Jin, head of the agriculture service department in the Ministry of
Internal Trade said the cotton market had become extremely disorderly,
characterised by panic buying, hoarding and rampant speculation, according
to a Reuters despatch.
Cotton is the one commodity whose supply and price is still controlled, but
the chaos in the market indicates that state control is unravelling.
Customs figures for the first six months this year showed that imports
reached 100,000 tonnes, a 14.8 per cent rise over the same period last year.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>CNZ  China, Asia.
