<HEADLINE>
FT  19 AUG 94 / International Capital Markets: CME seat changes hands for a
record Dollars 925,000
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURIE MORSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CHICAGO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A membership of the Chicago Mercantile Exchange's International Monetary
Market has traded for a record Dollars 925,000, a near-50 per cent increase
since the start of the year.
The transaction puts seat values at the CME above those at the New York
Stock Exchange, and demonstrates rising global interest in financial
derivatives markets.
Seat prices at the futures exchange have climbed steadily this year, largely
because world interest rate volatility has more than doubled turnover in the
CME's Eurodollar futures and options pits.
As the exchange's importance as a hedging centre for interest rate risks
rises, international banks which were slow in obtaining memberships are now
competing for seats.
Lloyds Bank, Deutsche Bank, and the Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce have
all bought CME seats recently. Exchange rules require a bank to own six
memberships before it can 'clear' or process trades for itself or its
customers.
Rising seat prices are also the result of an internal push to redistribute
ownership at the exchange.
The highly controversial plan would consolidate the exchange's two largest
divisions and shift governing power from a traditional base of agricultural
futures traders to the banks and financial institutions that now generate
most of the CME's business.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
