<HEADLINE>
FT  19 AUG 94 / International Company News: Northam posts loss of R129.7m
for first year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARK SUZMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Northam Platinum, the South African platinum mine in the Gold Fields stable,
has reported a loss of R129.7m (Dollars 35.2m) for the year to June, its
first full year of operations.
Production, at 1.15m tonnes milled, was well below expected levels and sales
revenue amounted to R238.4m against costs of R364.2m. The company, which
launched a R350m rights issue in 1992, has also used up its cash resources
as well as most of its R220m loan facility and has had to arrange a further
R25m loan to finance its losses.
The poor results were attributed to the mining area being far more
geologically unstable than expected. The situation had been aggravated by
the presence of high yield water fissures and fracturing to the east of the
complex.
Northam is currently carrying out a technical assessment to determine the
operation's future viability.
