<HEADLINE>
FT  19 AUG 94 / International Company News: Sales surge in mobiles is
Ericsson powerhouse
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BROWN-HUMES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A surge in sales of mobile telephone equipment powered a 78 per cent rise in
first-half pre-tax profits at Ericsson and led the Swedish
telecommunications group to strike a confident note about prospects for 1994
as a whole.
The increase in profits to SKr2.29bn (Dollars 290m) was better than expected
and stemmed from a 33 per cent rise in sales to SKr36.5bn and tight cost
control. Higher volumes rather than currency movements lay behind the strong
sales figures, Ericsson stressed.
Both the performance and a forecast from Mr Lars Ramqvist, chief executive,
that full-year profits would be 'significantly better' than last year's
SKr3.1bn heartened the stock market. The group's B shares rose 3.7 per cent
to SKr418.
The group's powerhouse is its radio communications division which has
achieved spectacular growth in sales and orders thanks to Ericsson's
world-leading position in mobile telephone equipment. Radio communications
sales were up 60 per cent to SKr17.1bn in the first half, well ahead of the
public communications division where sales advanced a more modest 15 per
cent to SKr11.5bn. Sales of mobile telephone systems and terminals were up
80 per cent.
The group, which has traditionally had higher research and development costs
than many of its rivals, stressed that costs relative to sales had declined
'despite continued heavy investments in technical development'.
A 19 per cent rise in the group's order book to SKr40.3bn showed it
continuing to make inroads into many of its most important markets,
including China, Sweden, the US, the UK and Italy. Although there was a
slight slowing in the pace of new orders between the first and second
quarters, the decline was less than some analysts had feared.
</TEXT>
