<HEADLINE>
FT  19 AUG 94 / UK Company News: Recovery boosts Dawsongroup
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON DAVIES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Dawsongroup, the truck and trailer rental company, yesterday revealed a 41
per cent increase in interim profits, as economic recovery was translated
into significantly higher utilisation rates for its fleet.
Pre-tax profits amounted to Pounds 5.02m for the six months to June 30, up
from Pounds 3.55m, on turnover ahead 14 per cent to Pounds 28.2m (Pounds
24.8m), reflecting the high proportion of fixed costs which means that
additional sales feed more directly into profits.
Profits from rentals increased by 46 per cent to Pounds 4.9m (Pounds 3.36m),
as utilisation of the truck fleet rose from 72 per cent to 87 per cent, and
average rates were pushed up by 4 per cent.
Trailer utilisation rose from 81 per cent to 84 per cent, and rates
increased by 6 per cent. There was also an Pounds 825,000 profit from the
sale of used vehicles, although management said such sales would slow in the
second half.
The company's performance was skewed towards short-term leasing contracts,
but it is increasing emphasis on contract hire (of one year or longer) to
improve earnings stability.
Commercial sales, primarily from the Volvo truck dealership, contributed a
reduced profit of Pounds 124,000 (Pounds 191,000), but the comparable figure
included used vehicle proceeds. On a like-for-like basis, profits were up 19
per cent.
Gearing at the interim stage stood at 118 per cent. However, capital
spending will more than double to Pounds 26m in the second half.
The group has just completed its first acquisition, in the form of the
Pounds 5.26m (including debt repayment) purchase of Morgan Varylease, a
vehicle and trailer rental company. Gearing is expected to rise to about 170
per cent by the year end.
Further investment may come in Europe, where expansion opportunities are
being sought.
Earnings per share were 10.8p (7.7p). An interim dividend of 1.8p (1.5p) is
declared.
COMMENT
Vehicle leasing is a business where success depends upon the management and
its control structures, and Dawsongroup has demonstrated a solid formula. It
has a substantial fleet with an average truck age of only 20 months, and has
successfully expanded product lines. It also boasts the rarity of never
suffering overall losses from asset disposals. High operational gearing and
solid management justify a premium p/e of 17.5, based on a 1994 profits
forecast of Pounds 10m; but there appears to be little more to go for in the
short-term.
</TEXT>
