<HEADLINE>
FT  19 AUG 94 / Observer: APR OTT
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Oh no, not the APR malarkey yet again. For those in ignorance - and
according to a 1993 Office of Fair Trading survey, half of us are in that
joyful state - APR stands for annual percentage rate, supposedly a useful
benchmark for assessing the cost of borrowing.
There are benchmarks, and then there are medieval banqueting tables fit for
Henry VIII. One FT reader is astonished to learn that Lloyds Bank calculates
an APR of 178.1 per cent for agreed overdrafts and one of 213.8 per cent for
unauthorised overdrafts on the bank's gold service payment card.
Lloyds explains that APRs for this type of card have been calculated on the
assumption of a customer being Pounds 100 overdrawn, for a full year, paying
no principal or interest, and incurring the monthly Pounds 8 charge. The
reader has written back to his Lloyds branch inquiring about rates on
deposits . . .
</TEXT>
