<HEADLINE>
FT  19 AUG 94 / Lloyd's agents optimistic on capacity
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Agents at Lloyd's of London expect the insurance market's capital base to
fall in 1995 but forecasts issued yesterday are more optimistic than had
been expected in some quarters.
The Lloyd's Market Board, which directs the market's business, said members'
agents and licensed Lloyd's advisers expected to be able to provide capacity
 -the amount of premiums syndicates can underwrite - up to a maximum of
Pounds 10.3bn in 1995.
Agents handle the affairs of individual Names, whose assets have
traditionally supported the market, while the advisers look after corporate
investors.
This year Lloyd's syndicates have an estimated Pounds 11bn in capacity. Some
agents have predicted that the amount of capacity provided by the Names -
about Pounds 9.3bn - would fall as much as 30 per cent after another year of
heavy losses.
Lloyd's reported losses of about Pounds 2bn for the 1991 year of account in
May, in line with its three-year accounting system. Several hundred of the
17,624 trading Names are expected to be unable to pay their losses, forcing
many to resign.
Corporate investors, who raised more than Pounds 800m last year, are
expected to raise more this year, partially compensating for the decline in
support from individuals.
It is still likely, however, that some syndicates could find themselves
short of capacity. The market board said agents were seeking about Pounds
11.5bn in capacity.
It said the market was 'not experiencing significant overcapacity although
premium rates have softened in an increasing number of areas'.
Separately, Lloyd's said that legal claims by hundreds of its Names from
North America were 'unfounded'. More than 400 Names allege that they are
victims of systematic fraud.
They will ask a federal judge in San Diego, California, to rescind their
Lloyd's contracts and discharge their multi-million dollar liabilities.
Previous cases against Lloyd's in the US failed when the courts there agreed
with Lloyd's that all grievances should be settled in a British court.
In the biggest action to date in the US, the Supreme Court ruled last
November that American investors could not sue Lloyd's for securities fraud.
A federal judge in New York had dismissed their action without ruling on the
merits of the case. More than 100 US Names were involved.
</TEXT>
