<HEADLINE>
FT  19 AUG 94 / Heatwave mixed blessing for shops
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sizzling summer weather last month boosted sales of soft drinks, ice cream,
summer clothing and garden furniture, but depressed business in indoor
furniture, carpets and electrical goods, the British Retail Consortium said
yesterday.
The data came as the Central Statistical Office announced that retail sales
volumes grew by a seasonally adjusted 0.4 per cent in July, compared with
June, and 3.8 per cent during the year.
Although these figures were slightly higher than in June, when the annual
volume growth was 3.3 per cent, City analysts said they painted a picture of
steady, rather than sharp growth.
Almost all the growth in last month's figures came from the food sector,
they said. Non-food retailers saw a small monthly fall in their sales
volumes, in spite of aggressive discounting, suggesting that consumer
confidence remained relatively patchy in the aftermath of April's tax
increases.
Mr Simon Briscoe, UK economist with Warburgs, said: 'The overall picture is
one of lower prices keeping volumes up, rather than strong spending growth
threatening higher prices.'
In the household goods sector, for example, sales volumes fell by 0.7 per
cent in July, compared with June, in spite of heavy discounting in this
sector. Measured on a three-monthly basis, sales values and volumes each
rose by a seasonally adjusted 0.9 per cent in the three months to July,
compared with the three months to April, indicating that prices in this
period had been flat.
The consortium said furniture and carpet sales were depressed in July by the
hot weather and a static housing market. Electrical and electronic goods
also performed badly, with sales marginally down on the previous year.
Although fridges and freezers sold well, demand fell for camcorders and
video games.
One household goods sector that benefited was the DIY market, which saw
strong demand for barbecues and garden equipment, the consortium said.
Sales at clothing and footwear retailers rose slightly, with volumes growing
by 0.2 per cent in July, compared with June, and 1.2 per cent in the three
months to July compared with the three months to April.
Seasonally adjusted values, however, were flat between June and July, and
grew by only 0.9 per cent in the three months to July, compared with the
previous three months.
</TEXT>
