<HEADLINE>
FT  19 AUG 94 / M4 weakness may help delay base rate rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mixed figures on bank lending yesterday gave a confused picture of the
strength of credit demand.
The annual growth rate of M4, the broad measure of the money supply, fell to
a seasonally adjusted 4.8 per cent in July from 5.6 per cent in June,
according to the Bank of England. This is well towards the bottom of the
government's 3 per cent to 9 per cent monitoring range for M4. Between June
and July M4 grew a seasonally adjusted 0.1 per cent.
M4 growth is one of the leading inflationary signs monitored by the Bank and
its weakness may further tilt the argument against an imminent increase in
the base rate.
However, sterling lending to the M4 private sector, which consists of all UK
residents apart from banks, building societies and the public sector, was a
seasonally adjusted Pounds 2.4bn in July. That is higher than the Pounds
1.6bn average recorded during the first six months of the year, although
down from Pounds 2.9bn in June.
British Bankers Association figures, which are compiled on a different basis
from the Bank of England statistics, showed that UK banks had increased
their lending in July to Pounds 1.4bn from Pounds 982m in June.
The association said consumer credit grew a modest Pounds 51m in July. The
increase meant, however, that consumer credit had risen for four consecutive
months for the first time since 1991.
Lending continued to be strong to the financial sector, which borrowed
Pounds 687m in July. Securities dealers, which borrowed heavily late last
year but which have been repaying debt since the collapse of the bond market
in February, borrowed Pounds 392m last month.
Non-financial companies, however, continue to be reluctant to take on debt.
The manufacturing sector repaid Pounds 255m of debt in July after borrowing
Pounds 148m in June.
Mr Don Smith, economist at Midland Global Markets, said: 'Lending appears to
be recovering at last but the progress looks very tentative. These figures
do not yet exude the confidence they should for this stage of the economic
cycle.'
Sales of machine tools rose in the second quarter but were below their
pre-recession peak, the Central Statistical Office said yesterday.
The volume of machine tools sales in the three months to June was 11 per
cent higher, on a seasonally adjusted basis, than in the first three months
of the year. Compared with the second quarter of 1993, however, sales were
only 2.8 per cent ahead, and about one-third below their 1990 levels.
Export sales rose 13.3 per cent quarter-on-quarter in volume terms, while
home sales increased 9.6 per cent. Total orders on hand for machine tools
showed a 2.4 per cent increase over the quarter but were 20.2 per cent down
on June 1993.
Letters, Page 12
</TEXT>
