<HEADLINE>
FT  19 AUG 94 / Kok completes Dutch cabinet
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RONALD VAN DE KROL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   AMSTERDAM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Dutch Labour party leader, Mr Wim Kok, yesterday finished choosing his
cabinet, clearing the way for Queen Beatrix to swear in the new government
on Monday.
The new foreign minister will be Mr Hans van Mierlo, leader of the
left-leaning D66 party, one of three parties in the new coalition.
Mr van Mierlo, who helped found the reformist D66 in 1966, served briefly as
defence minister in a short-lived coalition with the Labour party and the
Christian Democrats in 1981.
Mr Gerrit Zalm, the prospective finance minister, is a member of the
right-wing Liberals, the third party in the coalition, and is the head of
the semi-autonomous Central Planning Office. He has also been a senior civil
servant at the finance and economic affairs ministries.
Mr Kok's new government, which is committed to increasing employment and
changing elements of the country's generous welfare system, ends more than
three months of political uncertainty since May's inconclusive general
election.
The cabinet is unusual because it brings together three parties that have
never governed in the same coalition before and because its two main
components, Labour and the Liberals, have traditionally clashed on incomes
policy.
This difference of opinion could cause tension in future. However, the
coalition has already cleared one hurdle by agreeing on the broad outlines
of the 1995 budget, due to be presented to parliament on September 20.
The budget talks were part of the long and detailed coalition negotiations
conducted over recent weeks by Mr Kok, who was finance minister in the
outgoing cabinet.
His government programme is a careful compromise between the wishes of the
Labour and Liberal parties. He has managed to avoid cutting the level of
unemployment and disability benefits, yet he has also committed himself to
making spending cuts of Fl 18bn (Pounds 6.67bn) over the next four years in
such controversial areas as health and education.
Labour, which had been the junior partner to the Christian Democrats in the
outgoing centre-left government, saw a sharp drop in support in the May
poll, partly because of its agreement to previous welfare changes, but it
narrowly emerged as the biggest party overall.
The Christian Democrats suffered a historic defeat and now face being
relegated to the opposition for the first time since universal suffrage
began in the Netherlands in 1917.
It is still trying to find a replacement for Mr Elco Brinkman, who resigned
on Tuesday as leader of the party in parliament. Mr Brinkman is held
responsible for the party's electoral defeat, which was also caused partly
by the decision of Mr Ruud Lubbers, the veteran prime minister and Christian
Democrat politician, to retire from national politics.
</TEXT>
<XX>
