<HEADLINE>
FT  18 AUG 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Smaller stocks gain, blue
chips slow down
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
Small-capitalisation stocks outperformed blue chips yesterday as investors
continued to react to Tuesday's bold move to higher interest rates, writes
Frank McGurty in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 8.09 easier at 3,776.48, investors
having booked profits following Tuesday's 24-point advance. The more broadly
based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was up a scant 0.16 at 465.17.
Advancing New York SE issues outscored declines by 1,187 to 944 in brisk
activity, volume on the Big Board reaching 309m shares by the close.
In the secondary markets, the Nasdaq composite built on its relatively small
gain of the previous day, climbing 7.15 to 742.66. The American SE composite
ended 1.28 higher at 444.94.
For most investors it was a day to pause and reflect on the implications of
the Federal Reserve's aggressive tightening of monetary policy a day
earlier.
On Tuesday, the announcement of a move to lift two short-term interest rates
resulted in solid gains for stocks across the board, but not before the
market wrestled with worries over the impact of the policy change on
corporate profits. In the end, however, investors were able to shrug off
their concerns and focus on a welcome surge in long-term bond prices.
The positive mood in equities carried over into yesterday's trading, even
though the rally in bonds had stalled.
In both markets, investors were busy cashing in on the previous session's
gains, holding most of the leading stock indices in check throughout the
day. The Nasdaq was the exception as technology and heatlth care stocks
maintained their forward momentum.
There was no economic news on offer to influence sentiment, although it was
unlikely that any fresh data would have had much of an impact in the wake of
Tuesday's events.
In the vacuum, most stocks meandered. Among the big cyclical issues,
however, Deere advanced Dollars 2 3/8 to Dollars 67 7/8 thanks to favourable
comments by Mr Mitchell Quain, an analyst at Wertheim Schroder.
Caterpillar was Dollars  7/8 ahead at Dollars 109 3/4 , but International
Paper dropped Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 71 7/8 and 3M slipped Dollars  3/8 to
Dollars 54 1/4 .
Amid the general drift, American Home Products and American Cyanamid made
some waves with the announcement of a Dollars 9.7bn merger agreement.
After a delayed opening, Cyanamid jumped Dollars 2 3/8 to Dollars 96 1/8 on
news that stockholders would receive Dollars 101 a share in cash as part of
the deal. AHP's stock added Dollars  3/8 at Dollars 59 1/4 .
Retailing issues cooled off after Tuesday's heated session which was
highlighted by the release of a batch of quarterly results.
However, Toys R Us, which had climbed Dollars 2 on Tuesday, put on an extra
Dollars 1 3/8 to close at Dollars 37. Gap Stores retreated Dollars 1 3/4 to
Dollars 41 1/2 .
Kmart was marked up Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 18 1/8 in heavy volume of 4.2m
shares. After Tuesday's close the discount store operator announced plans to
spin off three of its specialty divisions.
Canada
Toronto stocks closed mixed with a negative bias after Tuesday's rate-driven
rally failed to produce any expected follow-through, in spite of a further
rise in Canadian bonds.
The TSE 300 index edged 2.48 points higher to 4,205.27 but falls led rises
by 391 to 314 after volume of 52.8m shares. Eight of the 14 sub-sectors
showed improvement. Strength in transportation and conglomerates was
countered by weakness in gold, forest products and oil and gas issues.
Mexico
Equities ended with only a slight gain after profit-taking erased most of an
early rally in response to sharply lower domestic interest rates, which fell
to their lowest level in almost five months.
The 37-share IPC index finished 5.05 points up at 2,699.65 after touching
2,732.45. Turnover was a heavy 2.77bn new pesos on 194.3m shares traded.
A trader said: 'Prices went up like crazy when interest rates fell and that
triggered profit-taking because the investors active in the bolsa now are
just speculating, the others are waiting for Sunday's (presidential)
election to be over.'
The interest rate on the bellwether 28-day Treasury bill fell 175 basis
points to 13.4 per cent at this week's auction. Analysts noted that
forecasts had been for a reduction of about 100 basis points.
</TEXT>
